April 1, 2023 marks the 20th Anniversary of Elephant and @thirdmanrecords is kicking off the celebration with Vault Package 55! Sign up to receive The White Stripes Elephant XX at the link in bio before January 31, 2023. The centerpiece of this set is an all new, direct-from-the-original multitrack tapes MONO remix of the entire Elephant album mixed by Jack White and Bill Skibbe. Additionally, two different mixes of Jack White's original solo demo "Hypnotize" are included in this one of a kind package. In conjunction with these 2 versions of "Hypnotize" is the original, first take version of "You've Got Her In Your Pocket" and all 3 are included on a stunning 7" single pressed on glorious glitter red vinyl. And of course, it wouldn't be a 20th Anniversary collection without a DVD featuring Elephant-Era Video Artifacts! Tying this illustrious Vault package together is a 28-page 12" x 12" booklet full of previously unshared photos from Elephant. Visit the link in bio to sign up and receive!

Revisit the making of Elephant in this Mono Mix trailer as part of @thirdmanrecords Vault Package Elephant XX. Direct-from-the-original multitrack tapes MONO remix of the entire Elephant album and mixed by Jack White and Bill Skibbe at Third Man Studio in Nashville, Elephant XX was executed on the same Calrec board used to complete the original stereo mix of Elephant at Toe Rag Studios in London back in 2002. “Jeff Beck, guitar innovator extraordinaire has moved to the next realm.  I wrote to him a couple of years ago to show him that I was standing where he once stood inside Sam Phillips studio in Memphis some 50 odd years before.  He was amazingly kind and instructional to me over the years.  Many shows that I’ve played began moments after listening to his song “Led Boots” backstage.  This bootleg clip that I’m posting is when I had one of the greatest thrills of my life, along with Meg White and Jack Lawrence of the Greenhornes, we were “the yardbirds” for one night backing up Jeff at the Royal Festival Hall in London. In our rehearsals he plugged straight into an amp, no effects pedals.  He was changing the sound of the guitar and doing things people didn’t know were possible from his earliest days on stage.  God Bless you Jeff, you must already be chatting with Cliff Gallup somewhere.” -Jack White III

#ThirdManVault Package 55: @thewhitestripes - Elephant XX includes a DVD featuring Elephant-Era Video Artifacts. Subscribe by January 31st at midnight CT to get this package - link in bio.

The footage includes the exact album take of Jack and Meg and Holly Golightly singing their hearts out so jolly on “It’s True That We Love One Another” and a previously buried multi-camera Japanese live performance of a wild show kicked off with an impromptu cover of the Stooges “I Wanna Be Your Dog.” From the insightful, unseen interview with Jack and Meg through beautiful 8mm film capture of the behind-the-scenes and making of “The Hardest Button To Button” music video, the collection here utilizes variety to convey the breadth and reach that The White Stripes covered in their dogged work supporting Elephant.

reposted from @jackwhiteartanddesign :

A few years ago I was lucky enough to be able to purchase the truck I'd always wanted, an original Ford Bronco. I never had any hangups about a particular year (hey this is a man who drove a Ford truck with no heat or windshield wipers in the winter back in the 90's), but I just hoped for a red one one day as I had been told I was brought home from the hospital in a red Ford truck after I was born. But nothing could prepare me for this find, a 1975 Bronco with Ranger package built on the exact day I was born in the city of Detroit! The slip said the phrase "Constructed between July 8th and 11th, 1975." Only 9,000 original miles on it as well, just incredible. So when Ford announced the Bronco was coming back I kept imagining the new version as a day to day truck parked right next to this in a generation spanning 2 pony stable haha! My hope was for a factory standard red with white top (just like the '75) , but not only was the white trim not an option, neither was actually getting ANY bronco due to supply chain issues (plug). I cancelled my order (which never came through), and bought one from a lot some ways away that had standard wild track package features (and was red with black trim). I got together with the talented folks at Greening Auto co. @greeningautocompany in Alabama to help me bring this design to life. The concept I had was to showcase two different versions of the same standard song, two generations of the same iconic truck. I didn't set out to make an exact modern replica of the '75 with things like replica hubcaps, chroming the bumpers and trim etc, but instead, an attempt at retrofuturism in a way, or perhaps "RetroPresentism"; the beauty of the same factory pushing out the same product just in different eras of pop culture. (Approximately one week after getting the truck back from the custom shop Ford announced a very similar looking "heritage edition"! I guess we think alike! But many design elements are not the same, and I'm still working on this. More details and photos to come in the next posts @jackwhiteartanddesign #fordbronco #jackwhiteartanddesign #retropresentism #bronco #greeningautocompany

To be born in another time, 
any era but our own would’ve been fine.
100 years from now, 
1000 years from now, 
some other distant, different, time.
one without demons, cowards and vampires out for blood,
one with the positive inspiration to foster what is good.
an empty field where no tall red poppies are cut down,
where we could lay all day, every day, on the warm and subtle ground,
and know just what to say and what to play to conjure our own sounds.
and be one with the others all around us, 
and even still the ones who came before,
and help ourselves to all their love,
and pass it on again once more.
to have bliss upon bliss upon bliss,
to be without fear, negativity or pain,
and to get up every morning, and be happy to do it all again. 

III

Some interesting items from the Third Man archives; Huddie "Leadbelly" Ledbetter's NYC criminal record and mugshot. This record only shows 3 of his many arrests. Huddie, according to folklorist and musicologist Mac McCormick, could possibly even be viewed as a serial killer. Mac once told me, "Those were just the murders that the authorities found out about." At the very least, not someone to mess with. Leadbelly (or "Ledbelly" as he is listed here) also amazingly was released from prison not once, but TWICE in his life for.....singing a song. With 'Midnight Special', 'Where did you Sleep Last Night?' and so many more, one of the greatest folk singers and songwriters in American history...just don't piss him off. #leadbelly

Third Man Records is announcing its second online auction, the Third Man Garage Sale: Collection from Third Man Records and Jack White. The auction runs from Tuesday, July 25th - opening at 2pm CT - through Sunday, July 30th and features collectibles and specialty items ranging from music gear and set props to furniture, vehicles, and much, much more, all straight from the label's storied archives and Jack White's garage. Notable inclusions are the White Stripes-era Framus acoustic guitar that was used in the "We're Going To Be Friends" music video, Jack's blue Ernie Ball St. Vincent guitar used on the Boarding House Reach tour, Third Man's cheese-shaped vintage CitiCar used to deliver the World's Fastest Record, gear from the Third Man Studio, props from the Consolers of the Lonely album shoot, Jack's personal Tesla, among other vintage odds n' ends and mechanical wonders. The auction will take place via Everything But The House's online auction (linked in bio), with a portion of the proceeds benefiting Detroit's Clark Park Coalition and the revival of this historic public space. #thirdmangaragesale #thirdmanrecordsauction #clarkparkcoalition #jackwhite #thirdmanrecords

Notes from Third Man Records Archivist Ben Blackwell:
A nifty lil’ Korg keyboard that was used live onstage by the White Stripes and still has the badass red-and-white road case to prove it. Is the Korg what Meg used when she played keys on ‘In the Cold, Cold Night’? Surely someone here knows the answer. This one has also been used in subsequent touring configurations since the White Stripes, easily noted by the Raconteurs logo sticker on the case. Additionally, this keyboard is actually painted White Stripes ‘red’ and was taped over with black tape once brought into the Raconteurs fold. How badass is that? Used live, in Europe, for both the White Stripes AND the Raconteurs. You’re welcome. A slick sounding instrument in and of itself without any of the historic connection or provenance. You seriously cannot go wrong owning this thing. It will change your life and most likely for the better. NOTE: British 220v power! This will not plug right into your American wall outlet, lest you wanna blow up the neighborhood.

Notes from Third Man Records Archivist Ben Blackwell:
Purchased by Jack White in Auckland, New Zealand on the White Stripes first ever overseas tour in November 2000. Jack had his eyes on the guitar, but with the asking price of eight-hundred New Zealand dollars, he left the store without pulling the trigger. John Baker, promoter of the tour (and soon-to-become long-time White Stripes tour manager) said “The New Zealand dollar is really weak right now. You should go and offer him $600 for that guitar.” With nothing to lose, Jack did just that and walked out the happy owner of this beautiful, redburst Framus Sorella model guitar with removable pickguard outfitted with pickups for electrification. Primarily serving as a backup (seldom used) during live shows, the guitar is most recognized for its use and appearance in the music video for “We’re Going To Be Friends.” Additionally, it is featured prominently in the 2001 White Blood Cells-era promo photo depicting Meg and Jack surrounded by a bevy of their red and white instruments. One time, roundabout March 2001 or thereabouts, at the end of a short string of shows I was helping the band load their equipment back into the house / headquarters at 1203 Ferdinand. For some long-forgotten reason, this guitar NEVER had a case. It was always just loose and unprotected. Anyways, carrying the thing with my left hand wrapped around the neck, close to the headstock, I manage to catch the neck joint of this Framus right on the door jamb. Put a decent crack into the thing. I’d goofed, big time. Jack looked at me and said “well, guess who’s not getting paid for this weekend?” Said crack in neck joint has since been repaired and while Jack’s resident guitar tech Dan Mancini has described the current state of the guitar as “rough shape but mostly working” it is worth stressing here…no other stage-used White Stripes guitar has ever been made available for sale. There’s a decent chance that none more ever will. Do NOT miss what might be your only opportunity ever to get your hands on a true piece of history from this iconic rock and roll band. Link in bio.

baskets weave, sawn wood, stove top, olive oil on butchers block, fresh cream, milk cream, heavy cream, boiled water steam, wood finish tung oil, baby's breath, tin foil; all in your hands with action, taking up time, pretending to work, but you can only do as directed by that unknowing person's whim, their deep breaths, sighs and annoyances, anything they want you would break ankles to find or provide, all because they looked at you.

Paused moments of frozen emotion, each figure a marble statue, each finger a spear, a knights sword. pointed right at you. eye lashes as propellers, winged ankles and sidewalks made of clouds, seconds, maybe even a second, that is second to none. they are there, and you are combined in love approved by any witness with no judgement. you have spent years yearning to receive it, seconds to achieve it, and the rest of your life to believe it. -jwIII

Desire and fear and how similar they appear and whether eyes always tell the truth. can they tell the difference? and is it any of their business? your eyes burning holes through the roof. desire IS fear, fear that you may not get what you want. the fear of rejection, negative inspection, or worse, the fear of being ignored, the pain and guilt from the possible need to resort to manipulation, the fear that you will never be good enough to receive the reward. sometimes we ARE good enough, but they dont' realize it. wringing our hands laying in bed as we toil and tumble and theorize it. we must be good enough for something. but what this is, can be hard to tell. sometimes it's a match made in heaven, and sometimes it's a comedy written in hell. - "Triple Fear" visual and written word pairing by JWIII.

From the Third Man Records archive: 2 of the rarest and most sought after British punk records In existence, the A & M Records "God Save The Queen" 45 first pressing and the EMI records black sleeve promo copy of "Anarchy In The U.K.". The "Anarchy" seven inch was a gift to Jack White from DJ John Peel from his personal collection and has a sticker in the corner that says "Sex Pistols" that is believed to have been labelling Mr. Peel may have done with his own records or the source from whom Peel received it. The black sleeves came only with the very first copies and both sides contain the Chris Thomas production credits that were changed in later pressings. The "...Queen" seven inch, arguably the rarest punk record in the world, was pulled before it could ever be sold, a mere handful of copies ever made it out into the world, some supposedly offered to A&M execs as a “golden parachute” upon the dissolution of the company. Music is not about snobbery and exclusiveness however, the artifact merely creates a connection for the listener or paints a beautiful picture of the environments the music was created in, at Third Man we stand and strive for preserving and sharing these moments of beauty in art whenever we can. #thirdmanrecords #thesexpistols #punkvinyl

From the Third Man Records Archives: Some of the rarest records of the incredible Led Zeppelin in existence! If you look closely at this sealed copy of Physical Graffiti you may notice different pictures in the windows. This was a very rare production of the record made exclusively for Chicago radio station WMET as some sort of Christmas give away. Bizarre that the band and Atlantic records agreed to this (did they?). Next we have the highly sought after Bob Ludwig mastered promo version of the band's second album. The story goes that Ahmet Ertegun's daughter played the first pressing of the "brown bomber" and her teenage record player couldn't handle the volume of the cut causing the needle to skip/jump. Ertegun ordered a new master made because of this incident making this version the holy grail of the album to obtain and hear. Next up, the rare UK stereo first pressing of the band's first album. If you ever see this record with turquoise lettering/logos at a garage sale, you would do well to grab it. And lastly a simple sealed first pressing copy of the bands third album. Third Man pushes to preserve and share the beautiful moments in vinyl record and music history and encourage discussion, but also most importantly to remind all that this music is always able to be enjoyed and studied in many formats by everyone. #thirdmanrecords #ledzeppelin #thirdmanarchives

‘ @thewhitestripes Complete Lyrics’ is now available from bookstores everywhere, Third Man Records storefronts, and thirdmanbooks.com. The deluxe, new hardbound book documents all of @officialjackwhite ’s original words written for the 6x Grammy Award-winning duo he and Meg White formed in 1997 through the release of their final album in 2007. The first-time-ever lyric collection also features never-before-seen and rare rough drafts, alternate lyrics, and photographs, alongside exclusive essays by @nifmuhammad , @official_ben_blackwell , and @caroranwill . You can find ‘The White Stripes Complete Lyrics’ today at your favorite bookstore such as those in the included map- Link in bio! Also available at Third Man Records storefronts and ThirdManRecords.com.

"Soda jerks were known for having their own lingo for how their drinks were made. They created nicknames for different drinks. For example they called a glass of milk “baby” and a strawberry milkshake “in the hay”. They also had lingo to express how they wanted their drink to be served. Coffee being called “draw one” would be served strong if called “draw one from the south”. If a drink was ordered with extra ice it was “Heavy on the hail”."

It is with the most humble humility that Third Man Records, in conjunction with Sony Music Entertainment and Sun Records, announces its 59th Vault package, Elvis Presley at 706 Union Ave: The Sun Singles 1954-55. Celebrating the seventieth anniversary of these monumental recordings, this collection includes faithful reproductions of all five of Presley’s original 7-inch 45rpm singles on Sun, pressed in a hypnotic yellow and black marble colored vinyl. Additionally, a bonus 7-inch EP of four Elvis songs recorded at Sun which didn’t see release until later are collected in a prime pretty picture sleeve and pressed on yellow and black “sun ray” splattered vinyl.

To further accentuate the set, we’ve included two linen-style postcards in the box, one depicting the classic, unassuming facade of the Sun storefront and the other showing, in glorious detail, the beauty of sound absorbing acoustic tile. Also added here is a name-tag styled patch spiritually inspired by the accoutrement of Presley’s truck-driving job at Crown Electric, extolling the titular hook of that first Elvis a-side. And finally, a substantive, milled nickel 45 adaptor, featuring the iconic rooster emblazoned on all those early singles.

Beyond that, ONE lucky customer will receive a package that contains original 1950s pressings of ALL FIVE Elvis Presley singles on Sun. Sought after by collectors for decades, these records’ value align more with precious metals than molded plastic. A true golden-ticket opportunity.

Order now through January 31st at www.thirdmanrecords.com/vault (Link in bio). Packages begin shipping in April.
